,"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Einion</i>, <i>ap Eynon</i> ‘son of <i>Einion</i>’. See   Eynon   and compare   Bennion  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Eynon","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>Enniaun</i>, an old Welsh personal name ultimately derived from Late Latin <i>Annianus</i>, but also associated with Welsh <i>einion</i> ‘anvil’, taken as implying stability and fortitude. See also   Beynon   and compare   Onion  ."]}]},{"name":"Llewelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]},{"name":"Llywelyn","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."]},{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Llewelyn ap Einion of Llwyn was born about 1235, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales as the son of Einion ap Llywelyn of Llwyn Melyn and Gwenvyr verch Phillip. He had at least 1 son with Leuca verch Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1235–":"umbes 1235–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1224–1316":"1224–1316","–Female":"Surnud","1316":"1316","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","about 1235":"umbes 1235","about 1255":"umbes 1255","Montgomeryshire, Powys, Wales.":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1235–":"noin 1235–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1224–1316":"1224–1316","–Female":"Kuollut","1316":"1316","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","about 1235":"noin 1235","about 1255":"noin 1255","Montgomeryshire, Powys, Wales.":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1235–":"environ 1235–Décédé","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1235–Female":"1235–Décédée"